Origin: Pop-weighted attribution of GP practice data
MetaDataNotes:
QOF prevalence estimates: The number of patients with stroke or transient ischaemic attack (TIA) per 10,000 patients (total list size). [Definition][Source: PHE][Source: NHS Digital]

Practice level numerator and denominator data for 2015 - 2019 inclusive was obtained (using API) and attributed to 2011 LSOAs using contemporary (annual) NHS Digital data on the number of GP patients in LSOAs [Github RAP script (R)], and attributed to 2021 LSOAs using population-weighted lookup tables [Method: Github R script - coming!].

Note: QOF prevalence data must be treated with some caution.

  1. They are based on data collected by individual GP practices. The data are likely to be generally reliable, but as GPs may not be equally effective at identifying or recording illness geographical variation may partly reflect GP catchment areas.
  2. QOF data are not age-standardised and thus age-sensitive conditions will reflect the underlying demography of populations. Areas with large student populations, for instance, will tend to have very low prevalence rates for most QOF conditions. Such notwithstanding, QOF data provide an insight into the local need for health services.
Comments: For QOF data see https://qof.digital.nhs.uk/; for GP population registers see https://digital.nhs.uk/data-and-information/publications/statistical/patients-registered-at-a-gp-practice

MetaDataNotes:
QOF prevalence estimates: The number of patients with coronary heart disease (CHD) per 10,000 patients (all ages). [Definition][Source: PHE][Source: NHS Digital]

Practice level numerator and denominator data for 2015 - 2019 inclusive was obtained (using API) and attributed to 2011 LSOAs using contemporary (annual) NHS Digital data on the number of GP patients in LSOAs [Github RAP script (R)], and attributed to 2021 LSOAs using population-weighted lookup tables [Method: Github R script - coming!].

Note: QOF prevalence data must be treated with some caution.

  1. They are based on data collected by individual GP practices. The data are likely to be generally reliable, but as GPs may not be equally effective at identifying or recording illness geographical variation may partly reflect GP catchment areas.
  2. QOF data are not age-standardised and thus age-sensitive conditions will reflect the underlying demography of populations. Areas with large student populations, for instance, will tend to have very low prevalence rates for most QOF conditions. Such notwithstanding, QOF data provide an insight into the local need for health services.
Comments: For QOF data see https://qof.digital.nhs.uk/; for GP population registers see https://digital.nhs.uk/data-and-information/publications/statistical/patients-registered-at-a-gp-practice

MetaDataNotes: One of the two components of the 'Indoors sub-domain' of the IMD2019 'Living Environment Deprivation Domain', the Housing in poor condition indicator measures the proportion of social and private homes that fail to meet the Decent Homes standard. The higher the value the greater the level of deprivation. [Report] [Source] [ONS Interactive Map] Published using 2011 LSOAs, of which there were 32,844 in England. As we are here dealing with 2021 LSOAs it has been necessary to assign the 2011 LSOA scores to 2021 LSOAs (n=33,755) using a population-weighted algorithm (Github RAP script (R)).
UniqueName: IMD2019: Housing in poor condition LSOA21CD
LongTitle: IMD2019: Dwellings failing Decent Homes standard (%)
